ution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Beatrix","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name, which was borne by a saint martyred in Rome, together with Saints Faustinus and Simplicius, in the early 4th century. The original form of the name was probably <i>Viatrix</i>, a feminine version of <i>Viator</i> ‘voyager (through life)’, which was a favourite name among early Christians. This was then altered by association with Latin <i>Beatus</i> ‘blessed’ (<i>Via-</i> and <i>Bea-</i> sometimes being pronounced the same in Late Latin).  See also  Beatrice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Beatrix von Reipersberg was born in 1059, in Bavaria, Germany, her father, Graf Kuno Von Reipersberg, was 30 and her mother, von REIPERSBERG, was 29. She married Arnold I Von Scheyern. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1124, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1059–1124":"1059–1124","1057–1104":"1057–1104","1083–1124":"1083–1124","1085–1135":"1085–1135","1087–1130":"1087–1130","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1093–1124":"1093–1124","1029–Male":"1029–Surnud","1031–Female":"1031–Surnud","about 1083":"umbes 1083","about 1093":"umbes 1093","1090":"1090","about 1085":"umbes 1085","1087":"1087","1031":"1031","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","um 1090":"umbes 1090","1083":"1083","1093":"1093","1029":"1029","1104":"1104","1059":"1059","1124":"1124","1135":"1135","1057":"1057","about 1087":"umbes 1087","Europa":"Europe","Sche